## üìù PART 2 ‚Äî EXAMPLES (SQL Queries Illustrating `DISTINCT` and Variants)
Assume we have a table `Customers`:
Customers
customer_id | name | city

1 | Alice | Mumbai
2 | Bob | Delhi
3 | Carol | Pune
4 | Dave | Mumbai
5 | Eve | Pune

### ‚úÖ Example A ‚Äî Distinct Single Column  
Get list of all distinct cities where customers live:
```sql
SELECT DISTINCT city
FROM Customers;

Result:
Mumbai
Delhi
Pune

Only unique city names; duplicates removed.

‚úÖ Example B ‚Äî Distinct with Multiple Columns
Suppose table has possible duplicates across combination of columns. Example:
Orders
----------------------------
order_id | customer_id | product  
----------------------------
1        | 1           | Pen      
2        | 1           | Pencil   
3        | 2           | Pen      
4        | 2           | Pen      
5        | 3           | Notebook 


If you want unique combinations of customer & product:
SELECT DISTINCT customer_id, product
FROM Orders;

Result:
customer_id | product
1           | Pen
1           | Pencil
2           | Pen
3           | Notebook


Even though there were two orders with (2, Pen), it's listed only once.
‚úÖ Example C ‚Äî Counting Unique Values
Count how many distinct cities customers are from:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT city) AS unique_city_count
FROM Customers;


Result: 3
‚úÖ Example D ‚Äî Use DISTINCT When Not Using All Columns
If you have a table Employees:
Employees
----------------------------
employee_id | name     | dept  
----------------------------
1           | Alice    | HR    
2           | Bob      | Sales 
3           | Carol    | Sales 
4           | Dave     | HR    
5           | Eve      | IT    


To get unique departments:
SELECT DISTINCT dept
